{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_yorkie_ver01/data/sn84026749/00280764747/1920123101/0573.xml":{"full_text":"ADVANCNG\nWASHINGTON'S INTER\n1921 Promis\nJames B. F\nBy JAMES I\ncharmais ef s seemd of Diroent.I\ncage and the First Tra\nThe year 1919 was still under tk\nthe Great War, while the present yes\nset in during the spring and it has nc\nnot likly to do so for a few more mo\nto be expected, but in prosperous tin\nwarnings of those who point out the\nbut act as if there never could be a cl\nIt is a well known fact that wit\nand decreases with a failing market.\nhugnwo failures, which, as I stated\nportant for some years, have increas\ncrease.\nThose undertakings which owed t\nstimulus of the war and intrinsically I\nnecessary for sound and conservative\nfor the' deficiencies. The failures a\nconce whose absence the business i\nDanger Now Due To I\nThe immediate cause of the decli\nthe present sharp business depression\nof the Federal reserv ebanks in inc\nmust always be noted that without s\ntinued inflation, which unquestionabll\na business depression such as we are\nspects resembles the on following 19\nhave had a catastrophe such as folloN\nThe danger at present is due cl\nEurope, it is estimated, owes this cou\nfour billions of dollars, as a result\nmerchants and bankers are finding i\nsuch as ought to take place at the pi\nthe foreign exchange market which I\nthere does not appear any immediate\nLIQUIDATION OF CREDIT\nNECESSARY.\nAs last year, the demand for bank\ncredit has remained steady and\nstrong and discount rates have ruled\nhigh. As a result, banks have had\nan opportunity to make large profits,\nbut these have been somewhat offset\nby the busir,ess failures to which I\nhave referred. Banks will serve their\nown interest best, and that of the\ncountry and of the world, if they con\ntinue to watch the situation closely\nand wherever possible urge their\ncustomers to liquidate so that credit\nagain may become iluid and be made\navailable to serve the necessary ex\npansion of production here and\nabroad.\nThere is no reason whatsoever to\ndespair at the present time. The\nworld has received a severe shock,\nbut not one from which there can\nbe no recovery. Fundamentally,\nsurface appearances to the contrary\nI notwithstanding, conditions all over\nthe world have shown progress and\nare likely to continue to do so. The\nyear 1921 promises to be a year of\nsteady though possibly very slow\nimprovement.\nMR. HAYNES HEADS IMPORTANT\nTRADE ACCEPTANCES COMMITEE.\nPresident Harry V. Haynes of the\nFarmers Mechanics National Bank\nof Georgetown, has been chosen chair\nman of the District of Columbia\nBankers Association Committee tn!\nTrade Acceptances, according to. an-1\nnouncement made today.\nGeorge L. Starkey of the National\nDank of Washington, George 0. Wal\nson. Liberty National Bank; Capt.\nJulius Peyser, Security Savings\nCommercial Bank; Erskine Gordon.\nContinental Trust Company, and lo\nbert V. Fleming, Riggs National Bank,\nare the other members.\nThe new committees will keep in\nelose touch with the national activi\nties in connection with the work of\nthe American Acceptance Council, co\noperating with the body whenever\npcssible.\nAmerican Banks for Mexico.\nPstablishment of seven American\nbanks in Metico is promised, accord\ning to a statement from the Mexican\nembassy.\n\"The American bankers are ready\nto invest in Latin America not ess\nthan a billion dollars in banks and\nindustries, ari Mexico has been\nchosen for theot Investments.\" the em\nbassy statement- declared.\nFINANCIAL\nFinancial Resolutions!\nAmong the many New Yesr\nresolutions new being 'aamed.\nnone is more essential to your\nweli-being than a sound anne\nOur First Mortgage Notes\nsnd the acid test of thu\nmost rigid requirements. They\nrepresent conservative loans\nand are secured on improv*d\nWashington real property, re\nenforced by continually' in\ncreaing equities.\nResolve to invest in theme\nNotes, because they are safe.,\neffer a liberal return and are\nat par every day in the year.\nSWARTZELL RHEEM\nHENSEY CO.,\n727 Fifteenth St. N. W.\nWAUWINGTON, D, C.\nThe Nsteen's Home Town,.\nPlace Tour Money\nin a financial insti\ntution that has\nstood the acid test\nfor ov thirty\nyears.\nUNION SAVINC.S\nBANK\n710 14th Street\nForeign Exchange\n'es Progress\nrgan Avers\nFORGAN.\ni the First National Bank of Chi\nt and Savings tBaak.\na influence of the boom created by\nr marked a reaction. This reaction\n*t run its course even now, and it is\nmths to come. On the whole, it wa\nes business men rarely regard the\nweakness of the existing situalion,\nange for the worse.\ni a rising market buying increases\nThe result of all this has been that\nlast year, had been few and unim\nd and are likely to continue to in\neir existence merely to the artificial\nLcked those qualities and attributes\nprogress are now paying the penalty\n0 far have been those of the weaker\norld need not regret.\niternational Situation.\nne in prices which has brought on\nwas undoubtedly due to the action\nrasing their discount rates but it\nich action we should have had con\nwould have finally brought on not\nnow facing and which in many ye\n)7, but in all probability we should\nred the years 1873 ad 1893.\niefly to the international situation\nntry on open book account roughly\nof which farmers, manufacturers,\ndifficult to liquidate in a manner\nesent time. The demoralization ot\nnotd last year is continuing, and\nprospect of relief.\nOST VALUE TO BE\nUSED IN TAX FORMS\nWerchants and Manufacturers\nWill Take New Basis for\nValuing Inventories.\nMerchants and manufacturers may\nLdopt \"cost or market, whichever is\nower,\" as a basis for valuing their\nnventories for 1920 income tax re\nurns -under regulations issued today\n>y the Bureau of Internal Revenue.\nrhe regulations also provide that the\ni fference caused by the fall of prices\nluring the year may be deducted-in\nLrriving at the value of stock.\nSecretary Houston and officials of\n:he Internal Revenue Bueau were\nvithout estimates tonight as to the\nlifference In revenues which may re\nmit from valuation at market rather\nhan cost. The belief was expressed\nn some quarters the difference would\n'un into many millions of dollars.\n[nternal Revenue Bureau officials ex\nlained that the law permits of a\nhoice of basis, and, under present\nonditions, \"market\" reflects more ac\nurrately the state of business condi\nons. To require inventories at a cost\nigher than \"market,\" it was added,\nvould1 be to put a tax on investment\nather than on income.\nUnder ordinary circumstances. \"mar\ncet\" is defined by the regulations as\nieaning the current bid price pre\nvalling at the date of the inventory\n'or the particular merchandise in the\nvolume in which ordinarily partici\npated by the taxpayers. The regu'a.\nAions, however, further provide that\nwhere, owing to abnormal circum\ntances, the taxpayer has regularly\n4old such merchandise at prices lower\nthan the current bid price, the in.\nventory may be valued at such prices.\nInventories of taxpayers on what\nwver basis taken will be subject tn in.\nvestigation, the Revenue Bureau an\nnounced, and taxpayers must satisfy\nthe bureau of the correctness of the\nprices adopted.\nTaxpayers are permitted under the\nregulations to value their iinvntoriem\nit co.t or market, whichever is lower,\nregardless of past practice, but in the\nruture a change will only be per.\n'nitted with the con-ent of the bureau.\nN. Y. CENRAL ASKS\nLEASE IN HICAGO\nRoad Ultimately Plans to Buy\nTerminal Properties for.\nProposed Extension.\nThe New York Central Rlailroad\n'mpany today filed an application\nwith the Interstate Commerce Corn\nnission for authority to lease, operate,\nLnd ultimately purchase the Chicago\nunction Railway c\"ompany terminal\niroperties at Chicago, Including the\nnion Stock Yarks Company.\nThe project contemplates the unifi\nation of related lInes to produce\nreater efficiency and economy in op\n'ration and involves properties valued\nat 532,000,000.\nThe lines embraced within the pro\nosed merger are needed by the New\nork Central to provide larger freight\nerminal facilities at Chicago.\nIn the consolidation the New Yorki\nentral will acquire terminal facili\nties which spread over the important\nindustrial districts of Southwestern\n'hicago, including the Union stocka\nyards district.\nIn the plan also are the terminal\nproperties of the Chicago River and\nindiana Railroad Company.\nThe proposed purchase price of the\nproperties was listed as follows:\nChicago Junction Rtailways, $22,917,\n00; Union Stock Yard Terminals, $10.\n45.000; Chicago River and Indiana,\n50,000.\nCLAIM BIG RAIL DEFICITS\nARE DUE TO COST OF COAl\nThe big deficits muffered by most\nof the New E'ngland railroads this\nyear were partly due to higher costa\nfor coal, the Interstate Commerce\nrommission was told today by repre\nsentatives of the rnads, in urginig re\ndjstment of division rates to pro\nvide larger revenues.\nD. S. Brigham, auditor of the lbs\nion and Maine rsilroad, aid that the\naverage cost\" for rosi during the firsi\nsight mo,nthq oft thiA year was 57.1fl\na ton. as enmparedl with $3.2% for the\n..A.es.m.Ai.n p...i-on of 1919.\nJSINE\nEASTMANATTACKS\nEXPRESSCONTRACTS\nCommissioner Claims Pact With\nCarriers May Grant \"Exorbi\ntant Profits.\"\nAltacking the contracturul re,ati;pon\nship between the Amerivan Htailway\nixpress 4ompany and the Vrincil)I\nrailroad comnpunies approved by inm\nIn1terotate Commerce Commission, lit\na divided opinion. Commissioner iHapt.\nman declared today. tAking i\"sue with\nhis colleagues, that the arrangement\nmny result in the granit of \"exorbi\ntunt profits\" to the express company\nand to the roads.\nThe contract approved. running\na period of five. years. was criticized\nby Commissioner Eastman on th-,t\ngrounds:\nI-That it is primarily a means\nwhereby the railroads guarantee th-,\nexpress company against loss. rathier\nthan offering a meams of insuring fai!\ncompensation to the railroads for\nprivileges and services they furnish\nthe express company.\n'.-That it is uncertain whether iin\nder the terms of the contract it will\nbe possible to yield fair compeniation\nto the railroads.\n.-That there is established a r:\nlationa4hip between the compensatio1\npaid to the railroads and the profit\nrece-ivel by the express company\nwithout any evidene- that such an\narrangement is fair and reasonabl*.\n\"In the absence of any evidence as\nto wvlhat fair compensation to the rAil\nroads may be,\" Eastman said, \"for\nall we know this contract may result\nin a grant of exorbit'4nt profits to the\nexpress company if fair compensati-in\nis to be paid to the railroads; or :t\nmay result in exorbitant profits to the\nrailroads if fair compensation is ti\nbe received by the express company.\n\"The record offers no means of ,i\ntermining with certainty which of\nthese alternatives we may favi-. jut\nthe express company probably will be\nthe lucky party.\"\nINCOME TAX RULING\nFAVORSMERCHANTS\nWill Be Permitted to Inventory\nStocks on Hand at Present\nMarket Prices.\nA measure of relief to merthants\nand manufacturers who have suffered\nbecause of the dec..a of prices, was\nextended by Internal Revenue Com\nmissioner Williams late yesterday.\nAn order was issued by Commis\nsioner Williams permitting manufac\nturers and merchants, in computing\ntheir income taxes for 1920 to base\ntheir 1920 inventory value of stocks\non hand at \"cost or market, which\never is lower.\"\nUnder this ruling merchants whn\nbought goods at high prices and are\nuinable to sell them at high prices will\nbe permitted to inventory their goods\nat the present market value and will\ncompute their incomes on the basis of\nan inventory of goods on hand at\npresent market prices.\nThe Internal Revenue Bureau wa.\nunable to compute the loss in taxes to\nthe Government under this ruling, but\nit was stated that it might run into\nmany millions of dollars. It was said\nthat the ruling was issued in order\nthat there might be equitable adjust\nment of income taxes and that mer\nchants and manufacturers might not\nbe required to pay taxes on profits\nwhich they have lost through the de\ncline in prices.\nThe ruling as applied to manufac\nturers includes stocks on hand or in\nthe process of manufacture, but does\nnot include goods in the process of\nmanufacture for future delivery at a\nfixed price.\nSEES AMERICA\nAS BLESSED LAND\nJudge Gary Says Business is\nMarking Time Until Read just\nment Ends, Then Big Trade.\nIn discussing the business situa\ntion in New York yesterday after\nnoon. Judge Elbert H. Gary, chair\nman of the United States Steel Cor\nporation, said that the large volume\nof business hoped for could not be\nexpected until the readjustment in\nprogress had reached a point where\nthere was a fair basis of selling\nprices so that the public would be\ninduced to buy.\nPrices in many cases he held to be\nstill extortionate, especially with ref\nerence to middlemen.\nHe emphasized that conditions\nwere abnormal, and that the Golden\nRule in business had been tempora\nrily suspended, but predicted that\nthis country would prosper beyond\nall others, \"not because we arec selfish\nor greedy, or would take any undue\nadvantage, but because, in spite of\nourselves, we have been blessed with\nthe greatest opportunity for success.\"\nMany of the evils which exist, the\ncriminal outbreaks in the large cities,\ndemoralization, greed, envy and cu\npidity he held to be a heritage of the\nWorld War,\nHe contrasted capital and labor,\nsaying of the former that the capi\ntalist had been endeavoring unrea\nsonably, if not unfairly, to increase\nhis wealth and that the workmen\nhad been trying to secure larLer\ncompensation for l.ess service.\n\"It is only repeating what many\nare at present saying,\" remarked\nJudge Gary, \"when I say that there\nare many things in the general at\nmosphere which are disquieting, and\nyet I am as hopeful and confident of\nthe future as I have been .at any\ntime. The wonder is that times have\nnot been much worse, Conditions are\nadnormal. The minds of men through\nout the world are distorted. This\nof course, is the result of the ter\nrible war through which we have\npassed, There has been an orgy of\nextravagance and profligacy.\nTelephone your \"Want Ads\" to the\nWashington Timem, they will be gives\nainestakring ere.\nSS AP\nNEW YORK STC\nQaWatIdms Rwwived I\n11:34 Tes\nHigh. o w A.M. Ciose\nkdv. Rumley-.. 14% 34% 14% 1416\nAjax Rubber 25 S16 2 W%\nAlaska Gold. 5 94\nAl-aka ens& 1 1 1 16\nAllaimr... 293 2 '9 6 25%\nAl.. Chem.. &Dy 44 43% 43\nAm. Agri. Chem. 16 t6% 56 15\nAm. Beet Sugar. 42 42 42 4016\nAm. Bosch...... 48% 47yj 47k 49\nA m. Car Idy. 119% 119'4 1tj 119M\nAm. Can .264 12 22 24\nAm. Can p.. 0 79 so 7s5%\nAm. Cotton OiL. 1711 17 17N 14A\nAm. Ice 42 42 42\nAm. Inter. Corp. 28@16 37 3$% 31%\nAm. Linseed.... 49 48 49 47\nAm. Loco. 8116 81 g1 81\nAn. Bafety Iazor 7 796 7% 7)6\nAm. Ship Co.. 8J4 8 8 76\nAm. Smelting 4344 234 34% 33\nAm. Steel Fdy.. :9 29 29 264\nAm. Sugar .....9 8W9% 893 90\nAm. Sugar pt... 964 US 964 99\nAm.SumatraTob 74 7316 74 7;h\nAm. Tobacco.... 113% 112N 113,%\nAm. Tel. Tel. 07 jb 7 4%\nAm. Wool....... (0% ES 60% 56%\nAm. Wr. Pa. pt. 30 30 30 303\nAm. 3ine.... 6% 6% 6% 656\nAnaconda 33 22N 32% 31%\nAtchison 83 83 53 836\nAtl.&Blrm'ton... 6% 636 6 Aj b)6\nAt. Coast LIne.. 86 66 (6 (bi\nAt.. 0. W. 1 74 714 73 76%\nAL G. A W. pt.. 43j4 3%' 43 46\nAustin Nichoss.. 9% 93 9% 9\nBalto. Ohio... 361 16 36\" 36\nBaL ho p.. -0% W 0% b0% b1%\nBaldwin Loco... 8b 6316 84 84%\nBethlehem Steel t24 52% 52% 6114\nBeth. Steel B... bil 54 54% 53%\nBrook Rapid T.. 104 I0 10 9%\nCaddo Oil....... 14 13A 14 136\nCanadian Pacido. 116 115 126 1lt14\nCal. Petrol...... 26 25 2b 2 1%\nCalumetAAria... 4034 40zi 404 40\nCerro do Pasco.. 25 25 2b 25\nCentral Leathr. 361K 3bg 36% 33%\nCent. Leather pf.. 84 64 84 83\nC